//             ----- Introduction -----
// This is an example Material.

// Any text placed after a "//" is a comment that will be ignored when loading this file.
// Whitespace in the definition of a Material will be ignored when loading this file.

//             ----- Understanding a Material -----
// A Material is collection of data that comes together to represent
// how a Mesh (3D Model) interacts with the lighting in the Scene.
// Meaning how you define a Material will change the colors of a Mesh,
// how shiny or dull looking a Mesh is, and how different lights "mix" on a Mesh.

// It is out of the scope of this example to explain how it all interacts, but
// there are plenty of resources online to learn from. (Search: Shader Materials)

//             ----- Defining a Material -----
// Only one Material may be defined per file.
// The Material gets its name from the filename, meaning this Material is called "example".

// The Material is enclosed in brackets
{
    // Each attribute must be in the formats laid out below, 
    // each ended with a comma if any attribute comes after.

    // Here we define the (Red, Green, Blue) values of the ambient, diffuse, and specular colors.
    //        (   R,    G,    B) | Max: 1.0, Min: 0.0 | Using a max of 4 decimal spaces (ex. 0.0000)
    ambient:  (0.8, 0.0, 1.0),
    diffuse:  (0.4, 0.0, 0.6),
    specular: ( 0.1,  0.1,  0.1),

    // Here we define the values of the ambient strength, and shininess.
    // Using a max of 4 decimal spaces (ex. 0.0000)
    ambient_strength: (1.0),
    shininess: (0.1)
}

// If there are any errors with the formatting, the program will catch it, alert you via the terminal,
// then apply a hot-pink material to catch your attention.